---
import RingDiagram from "./RingDiagram.astro";

const ring1Traits = [
  "Limited Hardware Access",
  "Only Non-Privileged Instructions",
  "Untrusted Code (User Applications)",
  "Least Privileged",
];

const benefits = [
  {
    label: "Memory Protection",
    body: "User applications (Ring 1) cannot access memory assigned to other processes or the kernel.",
  },
  {
    label: "Stability",
    body: "An application crash in Ring 1 remains isolated and doesn't bring down the whole system.",
  },
  {
    label: "Security",
    body: "Critical kernel data structures are protected from unauthorized modification, and malicious apps are contained.",
  },
];

const hardware = [
  { label: "CPU", icon: "cpu" },
  { label: "Physical Memory", icon: "memory" },
  { label: "Disk", icon: "disk" },
  { label: "I/O Devices", icon: "io" },
];
---

<section class="board" id="architecture">
  <h2 class="model-title">
    <span class="title-grad">Two-Level</span> OS Protection Ring Model
  </h2>

  <div class="board-grid">
    <!-- Decorative connector: kernel ring -> hardware resources -->
    <svg
      class="elbow"
      viewBox="0 0 100 100"
      preserveAspectRatio="none"
      aria-hidden="true"
    >
      <path d="M50 54 V 74 H 17 V 81" stroke-linejoin="round"></path>
    </svg>

    <div class="card cell privilege">
      <h3 class="cell-title">What is a kernel?</h3>
      <p>
        The word kernel is a term from operation systems programming. In that world, the kernel is where assembly code interacts with the computer’s CPU to do tasks, open files, and generally keep the computer running. From the CPU’s viewpoint, the kernel is the only program running on the computer; the apps that me and you use are not seen by the CPU. Instead, those apps make system calls to the kernel which does the work on their behalf. 
      </p>
      <p>
        In kernel-based development, engineers work closely with business people and operations people to codify the things that the business does. These business functions are called System Processes. The company then creates products (MCP servers, desktop app, mobile app) that make System Calls that trigger those processes. 
      </p>
      <p>
       Now any kernel will interact with systems outside of itself, like a database, the local file system, or a REST API server. These systems are described in the kernel via System Interfaces that present a facade to the System Process to consume. 
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="card cell">
      <h3 class="cell-title">How to leverage AI?</h3>
      <p>
        Kernel-based development lends itself very nicely to spec-driven development. Each piece of the kernel – System Commands, System Processes, and System Interfaces – lend itself very nicely to a self-contained spec. This spec then becomes the “source of truth” of how the kernel should operate. Using spec-driven development, you can then leverage AI coding tools to spin up different versions of the kernel in other languages. Let's say, you want to build a React Native app but your existing kernel is in Python. With AI and your specs, you can transpile that kernel into a Javascript library to embed in your mobile app. 
      </p>
      <p>
        But let's say, you don't want to rely on AI to make this core piece of your stack. After all, AI models are powerful at coding but can make costly mistakes. Maybe you would feel more confident if the kernel was hand-written. If that is the case, then you can still leverage AI for creating and maintaining the delivery platforms for this kernel. The development process is flexible enough so that brainpower can be devoted to what the organization deems the most important. 
      </p>
     
    </div>


    <!-- <div class="cell rings-cell">
      <RingDiagram />
    </div> -->

    <!-- <div class="cell usermode">
      <h3 class="um-title">Ring 1: User Mode</h3>
      <ul class="um-list">
        {ring1Traits.map((t) => <li>{t}</li>)}
      </ul>

      <div class="gateway">
        <div class="gw-call">
          <span class="lock" aria-hidden="true">
            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="15" height="15" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.8">
              <rect x="5" y="11" width="14" height="9" rx="2" />
              <path d="M8 11V8a4 4 0 0 1 8 0v3" />
            </svg>
          </span>
          <div class="gw-arrow gw-arrow-call">
            <strong>System Call Gateway</strong>
            <span class="mono">(e.g., `sys_write`)</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="gw-arrow gw-arrow-return">Return to User Mode</div>
      </div>
    </div> -->

    <div class="card cell transition">
      <h3 class="cell-title">Transition and Interaction</h3>
      <p>
        User-mode programs cannot perform privileged tasks, such as direct I/O
        or modifying memory maps. When an application needs kernel services,
        it must make a System Call.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="card cell hardware">
      <h3 class="cell-title">Hardware Resources</h3>
      <div class="hw-row">
        {
          hardware.map((h) => (
            <div class="hw-node">
              <span class="hw-icon" aria-hidden="true">
                {h.icon === "cpu" && (
                  <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="26" height="26" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linejoin="round">
                    <rect x="7" y="7" width="10" height="10" rx="1.5" />
                    <rect x="9.5" y="9.5" width="5" height="5" rx="0.6" />
                    <path d="M10 7V4 M14 7V4 M10 20v-3 M14 20v-3 M7 10H4 M7 14H4 M20 10h-3 M20 14h-3" />
                  </svg>
                )}
                {h.icon === "memory" && (
                  <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="26" height="26" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linejoin="round">
                    <rect x="3" y="8" width="18" height="9" rx="1.5" />
                    <path d="M7 8V5 M11 8V5 M15 8V5 M7 17v2 M11 17v2 M15 17v2 M6 11v3 M9 11v3 M12 11v3 M15 11v3 M18 11v3" />
                  </svg>
                )}
                {h.icon === "disk" && (
                  <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="26" height="26" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linejoin="round">
                    <rect x="3" y="6" width="18" height="5" rx="1.5" />
                    <rect x="3" y="13" width="18" height="5" rx="1.5" />
                    <circle cx="7" cy="8.5" r="0.6" fill="currentColor" />
                    <circle cx="7" cy="15.5" r="0.6" fill="currentColor" />
                  </svg>
                )}
                {h.icon === "io" && (
                  <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="26" height="26" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linejoin="round">
                    <rect x="3" y="5" width="18" height="12" rx="1.5" />
                    <path d="M8 21h8 M12 17v4" />
                    <path d="M8 9l-2 2 2 2 M16 9l2 2-2 2" />
                  </svg>
                )}
              </span>
              <span class="hw-label">{h.label}</span>
            </div>
          ))
        }
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="card cell note">
      <p>
        This call causes a software interrupt, triggering a controlled
        hardware transition from Ring 1 to Ring 0. The kernel validates the
        request and performs the operation with full privileges, then returns
        control. Faulty Ring 1 code cannot access Ring 0 directly, preventing
        a crash from spreading.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="card cell benefits">
      <h3 class="cell-title">Summary of Benefits</h3>
      <ul class="benefit-list">
        <li>
          <strong>Going too fast and breaking too many things</strong> AI coding unlocks a scale of code generation that was before impossible. As a result, codebases can grow at a pace that leaves human understanding behind. This is not a good thing. When developers don’t have a good mental map of what is going on in the code, bugs become harder and harder to fix and features become harder and harder to implement. Kernel-based development solves this problem by condensing down the most business critical processes into a single library. With a solid kernel, creating new features comes down calling the pertinent System Commands in the delivery platform. Hunting down bugs becomes easier because it is simple to look at logs and see if the error was generated in the kernel layer or in the delivery platform. 

        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Organizing engineering teams</strong> Businesses are running leaner since the adoption of AI coding tools. Let’s be honest, the tools have grown exponentially more useful in the last two years. They are no longer just a helpful auto-complete. Running swarms of agents, you can build just about anything that you want – if you are willing to pay the insane cost for serving these models. 

        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<style>
  .board {
    --ring-green: #4ade80;
    --ring-cyan: #38bdf8;
    padding: 12px 0 8px;
  }

  .model-title {
    text-align: center;
    font-size: clamp(1.7rem, 3.8vw, 2.5rem);
    font-weight: 800;
    letter-spacing: 0.01em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    margin-bottom: 34px;
  }

  .title-grad {
    background: linear-gradient(90deg, var(--accent-teal), var(--ring-green));
    -webkit-background-clip: text;
    background-clip: text;
    color: transparent;
    filter: drop-shadow(0 0 22px rgba(74, 222, 128, 0.25));
  }

  /* ---- Grid ---- */
  .board-grid {
    position: relative;
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 1fr) minmax(0, 1.3fr) minmax(0, 1fr);
    grid-template-areas:
      "privilege rings benefits"
      "transition rings benefits"
      "hardware note benefits";
    gap: 20px;
    align-items: start;
  }

  .cell {
    position: relative;
    z-index: 1;
  }

  .card.cell {
    padding: 22px 24px;
  }

  .cell-title {
    font-size: 0.92rem;
    font-weight: 800;
    letter-spacing: 0.05em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    margin-bottom: 12px;
  }

  .cell p {
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    line-height: 1.55;
    color: var(--text-secondary);
  }

  .cell p + p {
    margin-top: 10px;
  }

  .privilege {
    grid-area: privilege;
  }

  .transition {
    grid-area: transition;
    align-self: stretch;
  }

  .hardware {
    grid-area: hardware;
  }

  .note {
    grid-area: note;
    align-self: end;
  }

  .benefits {
    grid-area: benefits;
    align-self: stretch;
  }

  /* ---- Rings ---- */
  .rings-cell {
    grid-area: rings;
    display: grid;
    place-items: center;
    align-self: stretch;
    min-height: 440px;
  }

  /* ---- Ring 1 / user mode column ---- */
  .usermode {
    grid-area: usermode;
    padding-top: 36px;
  }

  .um-title {
    position: relative;
    font-size: 1rem;
    font-weight: 800;
    letter-spacing: 0.04em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--ring-cyan);
    margin-bottom: 12px;
  }

  .um-title::before {
    content: "";
    position: absolute;
    right: 100%;
    top: 50%;
    width: 56px;
    height: 1px;
    margin-right: 10px;
    background: linear-gradient(90deg, transparent, var(--ring-cyan));
    opacity: 0.6;
  }

  .um-list {
    list-style: none;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 7px;
    margin-bottom: 32px;
  }

  .um-list li {
    position: relative;
    padding-left: 15px;
    font-size: 0.82rem;
    color: var(--text-secondary);
  }

  .um-list li::before {
    content: "";
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    top: 8px;
    width: 4px;
    height: 4px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    background: var(--text-secondary);
  }

  /* ---- Gateway arrows ---- */
  .gateway {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 12px;
    margin-left: -36px;
  }

  .gw-call {
    position: relative;
    padding-left: 18px;
  }

  .lock {
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    top: 50%;
    transform: translateY(-50%);
    z-index: 2;
    width: 36px;
    height: 36px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    display: grid;
    place-items: center;
    color: #bae6fd;
    background: var(--surface-1);
    border: 2px solid var(--ring-cyan);
    box-shadow: 0 0 14px -2px rgba(56, 189, 248, 0.55);
  }

  .gw-arrow {
    line-height: 1.3;
  }

  .gw-arrow-call {
    clip-path: polygon(
      0 0,
      calc(100% - 18px) 0,
      100% 50%,
      calc(100% - 18px) 100%,
      0 100%
    );
    background: linear-gradient(90deg, #1e40af, #312e81 85%);
    padding: 9px 34px 9px 30px;
    text-align: center;
  }

  .gw-arrow-call strong {
    display: block;
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: #fff;
  }

  .gw-arrow-call .mono {
    font-size: 0.64rem;
    color: #c7d2fe;
  }

  .gw-arrow-return {
    clip-path: polygon(18px 0, 100% 0, 100% 100%, 18px 100%, 0 50%);
    background: linear-gradient(90deg, rgba(30, 58, 138, 0.55), rgba(15, 23, 42, 0.85));
    border: 0;
    padding: 10px 18px 10px 32px;
    width: 78%;
    font-size: 0.74rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: 0.06em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--text-primary);
    text-align: center;
  }

  /* ---- Hardware ---- */
  .hw-row {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(4, 1fr);
    gap: 6px;
  }

  .hw-node {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 8px;
    padding: 8px 2px;
    border-radius: var(--radius-sm);
    transition: background 0.18s ease;
  }

  .hw-node:hover {
    background: rgba(118, 146, 198, 0.05);
  }

  .hw-icon {
    color: var(--accent-teal);
    filter: drop-shadow(0 0 8px rgba(34, 211, 238, 0.35));
  }

  .hw-label {
    font-size: 0.66rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    letter-spacing: 0.06em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    text-align: center;
    color: var(--text-secondary);
  }

  /* ---- Benefits ---- */
  .benefit-list {
    list-style: none;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 14px;
  }

  .benefit-list li {
    position: relative;
    padding-left: 15px;
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    line-height: 1.55;
    color: var(--text-secondary);
  }

  .benefit-list li::before {
    content: "";
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    top: 8px;
    width: 4px;
    height: 4px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    background: var(--text-secondary);
  }

  .benefit-list strong {
    color: var(--text-primary);
    font-weight: 700;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    font-size: 0.74rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.04em;
  }

  /* ---- Connector elbow ---- */
  .elbow {
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    width: 100%;
    height: 100%;
    z-index: 2;
    pointer-events: none;
    opacity: 0.75;
    filter: drop-shadow(0 0 6px rgba(74, 222, 128, 0.6));
  }

  .elbow path {
    fill: none;
    stroke: var(--ring-green);
    stroke-width: 2.5;
    vector-effect: non-scaling-stroke;
  }

  /* ---- Responsive ---- */
  @media (max-width: 1100px) {
    .board-grid {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
      grid-template-areas:
        "privilege"
        "rings"
        "usermode"
        "transition"
        "hardware"
        "note"
        "benefits";
    }

    .elbow {
      display: none;
    }

    .rings-cell {
      min-height: 0;
    }

    .usermode {
      padding-top: 0;
    }

    .um-title::before {
      display: none;
    }

    .gateway {
      margin-left: 0;
      max-width: 420px;
    }

    .gw-call {
      padding-left: 18px;
    }
  }

</style>
